Two-Compartment PK/PD Model of R-Ibuprofen

PK/PD Model for S-Ibuprofen


1. Concept for the PK/PD model


We will construct a model for the Pharmacokinetic and Pharmacodynamic effect of the drug S-Ibuprofen that is going to be adapted from Simultaneous Fitting of R- and S-ibuprofen plasma concentrations after oral administration of the racemate by Ltsch et al.

The model we will adapt is on p.390 and is also attached to this file, highlighted in the red box.


Ltsch et al.Model

We will also adapt the equations present in the model.

  • Note: C(n) is just the concentration that can also be expressed as \(\frac{A[n]}{V(n)}\)).


We can design our conceptual model through this info:



Type of Model


The PK model will be a four-compartment Bolus oral model

  1. The Initial depot for the drug, or the GI tract.

  2. The central compartment, or blood plasma.

  3. A peripheral compartment where some of the drug will perfuse.

  4. The effect compartment or the Biophase where the drug will administer the effect.

Note:

  • Bolus denotes that there will be a single given within a short amount of time.
    • Since the drug is taken in pill form, the dose is bolus.
  • Biophase denotes that the drug will go to a compartment before it can finally administer its effects.




2. Description of Approach


Modeling PK


Pharmacokinetics refers to the biophysical process that occurs from a drugs ingestion or injection until it is excreted.

Often, the acronym ADME is used to describe pharmacokinetics and is an abbreviation of:

  • Absorption
  • Distribution
  • Metabolism
  • Excretion


How are these parameters correlated to ADME


  • Dose:
    • The dose(A) is the initial amount of dose that is administered (usually in mg).
    • It undergoes multiple changes as the dose is absorbed and distributed in compartments.
  • Absorption:
    • Refers to how the drug is absorbed into the system per time(hrs-1) or the absorption rate (ka).
  • Distribution:
    • Refers to how much of the drug is distributed in the system, or the volume(L) of distribution(Vd).
    • Since the system has two compartments where the drug is distributed, we will use V and V2 to the Vd for compartments 1 and 2, respectively.
  • Metabolism/Excretion:
    • Both concern themselves with the elimination of the drug from the system.
    • The primary metric for this step is clearance(CL), or the amount of drug removed per set time (L/hr).
    • Q and is the rate of transfer between compartments (L/hr), and acts like clarence by removing dose from a compartment.

Parameters will be extracted from the PK the S-Ibuprofen parameters from Ltsch et al.p.395 Table 2.


Setting Up the PK Equations


We can use the equations in the arrows we adapted from Ltsch et al.to set up additional equations that show the change of dose over time for each compartment.

If we take in the parameters and our model, we can construct the PK portion of our equations by writing the dose change per each of the numbered steps in the concept model.

  1. Absorption of the dose:
    • \(\frac{d[A_1]}{dt} = -k_a [A_1]\) or the dose change per time from the GI tract as it is being absorbed into the blood plasma from the GI tract.
  2. Distribution in the central compartment:
    • \(\frac{dA_2}{dt} = k_a A_1 - \frac{CL}{V} A_2+ Q\!\left(\frac{A_3}{V_2} - \frac{A_2}{V}\right)\), or the change of dose in the blood plasma.
    • We see the dose go up as the drug is absorbed in the plasma.
    • However, that dose is modified by the clearance of the drug and the inter compartmental transfer between the plasma and the peripheral compartment
  3. Distribution in the peripheral compartment:
    • \(\frac{dA_3}{dt} = Q\left(\frac{A_2}{V} - \frac{A_3}{V_2}\right)\) refer to the change of the dose in the third compartment as we account for the inter compartmental transfer factor



Modeling PD


PD is the measure of the efficacy of the drug over concentration.

However, in our model, we will measure the efficacy over time as we want to integrate PK and PD.

Therefore, we will be measuring the efficacy of the drug as a percentage of the maximum desired efficacy over time.


Setting Up the PD equation


Based on the model, we will need to use the change in concentration per time in blood plasma (\(\frac{dA[2]}{V}\)) as it enters the effect compartment.

For A[4], the concentration will effectively be the same as the dose since the drug is not distributed in the compartment but going toward the area of effect.

We will then need to account for the concentration where we will reach half efficacy or \(EC_{50}\)(mg/L). - So when \(EC_{50}\) = \(\frac{dA[2]}{V}\), the efficacy will be 0.5 or 50%.

Since we are using a Biophase equation, we would need to account for the delay between taking from plasma to the effect compartment. - We can represent this delay through the factor ke0 (hrs-1).

Finally, we will multiply by EFF or 100% to get our percent of efficacy.

We can put this together through the equation:

4.\(\frac{dE}{dt} = k_{e0} \left[ \frac{E_{\text{FF}} \, (A_2 / V)}{EC_{50} + (A_2 / V)} - A_4 \right]\), PD parameters for ke0 and \(EC_{50}\) will be extracted from Ltsch et al.p.389 and Figure.4.

## How to begin our simulation

Creating the model based on our derrived equation from Part 2


To start our model we need to set up the set of equations that the model will go through using new_ode_model.

There are many ways we can use new_ode_model:

  1. We can run it without an argument and see all available packages.

    • Unfortunately, many of these packages are primarily for PK.

  2. We can also load a model from a file that already has a code in it.

  3. However, we will be using the new_ode_model function code to add our equations in a pseudo-code format.

When using the code function, we have to abide by certain constraints:

  • the derivatives in the ODE system are defined using dAdt.
  • the corresponding dose in each compartment needs to contain the appropriate number [ ].
  • equations are defined using =.

We can then begin to define additional parameters of the code, such as: - state_int, which will set up the initial concentrations of the doses in their respective compartments.

  • obs, will set uo the compartment we are observing.

    • In our PK model, this may be the second compartment (cmt=2)

    • In that case, to get the concentration, we will need to scale with the distribution volume parameter for that compartment, V (scale = V)

    • We can write this as a list function for our observations

  • dose, can be used to specify the compartment(cmt=1) the dose is administered and the bioavalibility (bioav =1) of the dose.

    • This can be set up as a list as well.


pkpdmodel_ibuprofen_pkdata <- new_ode_model(code = "
    dAdt[1] = -KA * A[1]
    dAdt[2] = KA * A[1] -(CL/V) * A[2] + (Q/V2)*A[3] - Q/V*A[2]
    dAdt[3] = -(Q/V2)*A[3] + (Q/V)*A[2]
    conc= A[2]/V
    dAdt[4] = ke0 * (EFF*conc)/(conc+EC50) - ke0*A[4]
  ", 
                           state_init = "A[4] = 0;", 
                           
                           obs = list(cmt = 2, scale = "V"),
                           
                           dose = list(cmt = 1, bioav = 1)
)


Setting up parameters


To add our parameters,, we can simply create a list function that incorporates the parameters that we extracted from Ltsch et al.


pk_pd_ibu_pain <- list(   # the parameters for the PD simulation for Pain ratings 
  "KA" = 1.52,
  "V" = 5.45,
  "V2"= 5.2,
  "CL" = 4.64,
  "Q"= 4.1,
  "EFF"=100,
  "EC50"=24.4,
  "ke0"=1.1
)


pk_pd_ibu_ep <- list(   # the parameters for the PD simulation for Evoked potentials 
  "KA" = 1.52,
  "V" = 5.45,
  "V2"= 5.2,
  "CL" = 4.64,
  "Q"= 4.1,
  "EFF"=100,
  "EC50"=8.71,
  "ke0"=0.27
)


Setting Up a Regiment


To set up our regiment we can use the command new_regimen() to provide dose amount(mg) and number of doses(n).

  • For multiple doses, we may also add a dosing interval (interval=number) or a times vector that has all the times that multiple doses will be administered.

Our model will need one dose of 400mg S-Ibuprofen in one interval.


reg_ibu <- new_regimen( # the drug regiment
  amt = 400,
  interval = 10,
  n = 1
)


Setting Up the number of individuals


n_ibu_trial<- 12 #number of individuals tested



Simulating the data


To simulate PKPD data, we will need to use the sim() function, which will simulate the model function we set up with new_ode_model. The data will then be saved into a data.frame, which we can then graph.

When setting up the sim() function, we will need to add all of our previous metrics and a few additional metrics to help us generate better data.

For this model, we will only need to define two necessary metrics:

  1. The time points that data has been recorded. This can be done using the t_obs = command, where the time points can be entered through a vector.
    • We have extracted the times of observations from Ltsch et al.p.388.
  2. The Omega Matrix or Variability between the parameters based on the number of individuals. It could be written as either a vector, or we can specify the variability of a parameter by using cv_to_omega(list( and have a parameter = SD between individual parameters.
    • Variability is optional. However, it is necessary to add randomness to simulations.
    • Since Ltsch et al.do not provide us with a variability matrix SD between the parameters, we have instead chosen to run the parameters with very low SDs as they do not have high SDs with our PK and PD models. 
pkpdsimvalues_ibu <- sim_ode(
  ode = pkpdmodel_ibuprofen_pkdata,
  n_ind = n_ibu_trial,
  omega = cv_to_omega(
    par_cv = list(CL = 0.1, V = 0.1, V2 =0.125, Q = 0.2, ke0 = 0.05)), # the omega matrix is the subject variability for the parameters 
  parameters = pk_pd_ibu_pain,
  regimen = reg_ibu ,
  t_obs = c(0, 0.167,.33, .5, .75, 1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10) #timepoints of the observation
)
## No parameter list provided as argument, assumed order for `omega_matrix`: CL, V, V2, Q, ke0

>Let us now plot the PK results:



PK data analysis


In addition to the plot, we can use the observation data to measure the Cmax, tmax and AUC for the PK curve to help us compare with the data from from Ltsch et al. 

mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time <- pkpdsimvalues_ibu_pkobs %>% group_by(t) %>% summarise(sdev=sd(y), y=mean(y))
Cmax <- max(mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time$y)
sdev_cmax <-mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time$sdev[which.max(mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time$y)]
tmax <- mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time$t[which.max(mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time$y)]
mean_ibu_pkobs_per_conc <- pkpdsimvalues_ibu_pkobs %>% group_by(y) %>% summarise(sdev=sd(t))


#for the AUC we can use a for loop to summarize the AUC for each timepoint using a trapezoidal calculation
mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time$AUC <- 0
auc <- 0

for (i in 2:14) {
  t1 <- mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time[i-1, "t"]
  t2 <- mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time[i, "t"]
  y1 <- mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time[i-1, "y"]
  y2 <- mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time[i, "y"]
  
  auc <- auc + ((y2 + y1) / 2) * (t2 - t1)
  mean_ibu_pkobs_per_time$AUC[i] <- auc
}

print(Cmax)
## [1] 27.39138
print(sdev_cmax)
## [1] 2.335595
print(tmax)
## [1] 0.75
print(auc)
##          y
## 1 83.47117


>We can now set up the PK statistical measurement data alongside the results from Ltsch et al.

  • SD for tmax and AUC are not included as we could not find the right code for them.

    • We can note that the tmax SD may be relatively low as the majority of the high concentration values lie around 0.75, with a few occasionally being 0.5.

    • For AUC, we believe that the standard rage that resulted from multiple simulations has a range from about 76 to 90, giving it a standard deviation that is lower than that of Ltsch et al.


#let's set up a table to compare the two 

Ltsch_et_al. <- c(20, 2.9, 1, .57, 67.5, 14.9)
PK_model<- c(Cmax, sdev_cmax, tmax, 0, auc, 0)
PKstats <- rbind (Ltsch_et_al., PK_model)
colnames(PKstats) <- c("Cmax(mg/L)", "SD_Cmax", "tmax(h)", "SD_tmax", "AUC(mg h/L)", "SD_AUC")
print(PKstats)

Plotting the PD data


For PD data we have to slightly tweak the observation compartment in our original new_ode_model function to set the fourth compartment (cmt = 4) as our observation compartment and remove any scaling (scale = 1).


pkpdmodel_ibuprofen_pddata <- new_ode_model(code = "
    dAdt[1] = -KA * A[1]
    dAdt[2] = KA * A[1] -(CL/V) * A[2] + (Q/V2)*A[3] - Q/V*A[2]
    dAdt[3] = -(Q/V2)*A[3] + (Q/V)*A[2]
    conc= A[2]/V
    dAdt[4] = ke0 * (EFF*conc)/(conc+EC50) - ke0*A[4]
  ", 
                                            state_init = "A[4] = 0;", 
                                            
                                            obs = list(cmt = 4, scale = 1),
                                            
                                            dose = list(cmt = 1, bioav = 1)
)


To setup our sim()function for PD, we can just change the ode= to the PD model:


pkpdsimvalues_ibu_pdobs_pain <- sim_ode(

PD data analysis


>We can set up functions to calculate Emax and tmax_eff for the PD data like we did with the PK data.

AUC will not be necessary since Ltsch et al.did not provide much statistical analysis for the PD data.

We can measure the maximum efficacy and maximum time of efficacy for Pain Ratings to see how each of the models changes over time.


mean_ibu_pdobs_per_time_pain <- pkpdsimvalues_ibu_pdobs_pain %>% group_by(t) %>% summarise(sdev=sd(y), y=mean(y))
Emax_pain <- max(mean_ibu_pdobs_per_time_pain$y)

tmax_eff_pain <- mean_ibu_pdobs_per_time_pain$t[which.max(mean_ibu_pdobs_per_time_pain$y)]

4. Results & Interpretation



Comparing PK data with Ltsch et al.



Ltsch_et_al. <- c(20, 2.9, 1, .57, 67.5, 14.9)
PK_model<- c(Cmax, sdev_cmax, tmax, 0, auc, 0)
PKstats <- rbind (Ltsch_et_al., PK_model)
colnames(PKstats) <- c("Cmax(mg/L)", "SD_Cmax", "tmax(h)", "SD_tmax", "AUC(mg h/L)", "SD_AUC")
print(PKstats)
##               Cmax(mg/L) SD_Cmax  tmax(h) SD_tmax AUC(mg h/L) SD_AUC
## Ltsch_et_al. 20         2.9      1       0.57    67.5        14.9  
## PK_model      27.39138   2.335595 0.75    0       83.47117    0


Both graphs maintain a similar curve shape.

However, if we were to look at the statistical analysis between the two, we would notice that the PK/PD model has a few significant differences compared to Ltsch et al.:

  • It appears that Cmax is higher in the PK/PD model than in the Ltsch et al.model. However, both seem to be within the same range, and standard devition

  • tmax is lower in the PK/PD model by about 15 minutes.

    • A possible explanation could be the lag time described by Ltsch et al., which would have been difficult to implement in PKPDsim.
    • However, both values appear to be within range of each other, and the dependency may just be due to the lag time

  • AUC is also significantly more prominent in the PK/PD model, most likely due to the higher concentration values

    • However, the SD for the AUC of Ltsch et al.may signify that their results had significant variance.
    • With an average of 67.5 and 14.9 SDs, many of their values may be closer to this models AUC



## Comparing PD data with Ltsch et al.



As mentioned previously, there is no statistical analysis for the PD aspect of their data, and therefore, there can be no additional comments.


However, there appears to be an issue with the results since the graphs generated by the PK/PD model appear to be opposite of those in Ltsch et al.. This could stem from an error in the code or a mistake from Ltsch et al.We are more inclined to believe in the latter as an \(EC_{50}\) value of 8.71mg/L will have a significantly longer duration than an \(EC_{50}\) value of 24.37mg/L since the concentration of S-Ibuprofen Plasma Concentration vs.Time is less likely to maintain a value above 24.37mg/L for long. Therefore, the efficiency will rapidly decrease after a few hours of peak. We can see this occurring at around 1-hour post-drug administration based on the S-Ibuprofen Plasma Concentration vs.Time graph. This occurrence is also consistent with the S-Ibuprofen %Eff in Pain Ratings vs.Time as we see the Emax of the simulation peaks at tmax_eff of 2 hours. Meanwhile, the concentration of S-ibuprofen in the blood plasma is more likely to maintain a value of 8.71mg/L throughout most of the trial run. The concentration goes below 8.71mg/L only after 4 hours in the S-Ibuprofen Plasma Concentration vs.Time graph can be correlated to S-Ibuprofen %Eff in Evoked Potentials vs Time where we see the tmax_eff of 4 hours.
